>mkpop3dcert</H1
><DIV
CLASS="REFNAMEDIV"
><A
NAME="AEN10"
></A
><H2
>Name</H2
>mkpop3dcert&nbsp;--&nbsp;create a test SSL certificate for POP3 over SSL</DIV
><DIV
CLASS="REFSYNOPSISDIV"
><A
NAME="AEN13"
></A
><H2
>Synopsis</H2
><P
><B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>@sbindir@/mkpop3dcert</B
></P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="REFSECT1"
><A
NAME="AEN16"
></A
><H2
>DESCRIPTION</H2
><P
>POP3 over SSL requires a valid, signed, X.509 certificate.  The default
location for the certificate file is
<TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>@datadir@/pop3d.pem</TT
>.
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>mkpop3dcert</B
> generates a self-signed X.509 certificate,
mainly for
testing.
For production use the X.509 certificate must be signed by a
recognized certificate authority, in order for mail clients to accept the
certificate.</P
><P
><TT
CLASS="FILENAME"
>@datadir@/pop3d.pem</TT
> must be owned by the
@mailuser@ user and
have no group or world permissions.
The <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>mkpop3dcert</B
> command will
enforce this.  To prevent an unfortunate accident,
<B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>mkpop3dcert</B
>
will not work if <B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>@datadir@/pop3d.pem</B
> already exists.</P
><P
><B
CLASS="COMMAND"
>mkpop3dcert</B
> requires
<TT
CLASS="APPLICATION"
>OpenSSL</TT
> to be installed.</P
></DIV
><DIV
CLASS="REFSECT1"
><A
NAME="AEN29"
></A
><H2
>FILES</H2
><P
></P
><DIV
CLASS="VARIABLELIST"
><DL
><DT
>@datadir@/pop3d.pem</DT
><DD
><P
>X.509 certificate.</P
></DD
><DT
>@sysconfdir@/pop3d.cnf</DT
><DD
><P
>Parameters used by OpenSSL to
create the X.509 certificate.</P
></DD
></DL
></DIV
